<BlogPost
	title="The Ultimate Guide to Old Orchard Beach, Maine"
	description="Seven miles of beach, a 475-foot wooden pier, and one of the last traditional amusement parks on the New England coast. Everything you need to know before your first — or tenth — visit."
	date="April 2026"
	category="Destination Guide"
	slug="things-to-do-old-orchard-beach"
>
	<p>Old Orchard Beach sits at the southern end of Saco Bay, about 15 miles south of Portland. It's part Coney Island, part classic New England, with a genuinely working-class summer energy — loud, fun, and unapologetically built for having a good time. Here's what to do, where to eat, and how to understand the place before you arrive.</p>

	<h2>The Beach</h2>

	<p>The continuous sandy beach stretches <strong>seven miles</strong> from Pine Point in Scarborough to Camp Ellis in Saco — the longest continuous sandy beach in Maine. Old Orchard is wide, flat, and gently sloping, positioned in a sheltered cove on Saco Bay. Wave action is typically gentle, making it excellent for families with small children.</p>

	<p>The sand is white and fine, notably cleaner and more abundant than rockier Maine beaches to the north. This is a social beach: volleyball, frisbee, sandcastles, people-watching. Don't come here for solitude — come here for the full summer experience.</p>

	<p><strong>Water temperatures:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>June: 55–60°F — cold, but people brave it</li>
		<li>July: 60–65°F — cool but swimmable; most people go in</li>
		<li>August: peaks around 64–68°F — the most comfortable swimming</li>
		<li>September: often still 60–65°F, sometimes better than July</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>The Pier</h2>

	<p>The Pier is the centerpiece of Old Orchard Beach. The current structure is 500 feet long, extending directly over the Atlantic from the foot of Old Orchard Street. It was first built in 1898 — the original version stretched nearly 1,825 feet with three pavilions and a casino at the end. Frank Sinatra, Louis Armstrong, and Benny Goodman all played the Pier Casino Ballroom in its heyday. The Blizzard of 1978 destroyed most of what remained; the current pier was rebuilt and reopened in 1980.</p>

	<p>Today the pier has souvenir shops, food vendors, and restaurants. At the far end: a nightclub with a Sunset Deck and Atlantic views. <strong>Reader's Digest named it one of the Top 5 Beach Boardwalks in the US in 2021.</strong></p>

	<p><strong>On the pier:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Pier French Fries</strong> — open since 1932; the mandatory OOB food stop</li>
		<li><strong>Bill's Pizza</strong> — operating since 1949</li>
		<li><strong>Hooligan's Landing</strong> — seafood restaurant at the pier entrance</li>
		<li><strong>Top of the Pier Nightclub</strong> — with a Sunset Deck and ocean views</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Palace Playland</h2>

	<p>New England's only remaining beachfront amusement park has operated on the same 5-acre site since 1902. More than 28 rides plus Maine's largest arcade — 24,000 square feet with over 200 games. Free to enter; pay per ride or buy a day pass.</p>

	<p><strong>Rides worth knowing:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Electra Wheel (Giant Ferris Wheel)</strong> — over 70 feet tall; views of the Atlantic and the full 7-mile beach at sunset</li>
		<li><strong>Adrenalin</strong> — the park's roller coaster</li>
		<li><strong>Speedy Coaster</strong> — new for 2026, with smooth twists and hills</li>
		<li><strong>Wind Surfer</strong> — three-person hang glider lifting 30 feet in the air</li>
		<li><strong>Nitro Speed</strong> — spins and orbits cars around a central hub with lights and music</li>
		<li><strong>Drop Zone</strong> — tower drop</li>
		<li><strong>Wave Swinger, The Pirate, Bumper Cars, Carousel</strong></li>
	</ul>

	<p>Season runs late May through Labor Day. Weekday hours: Noon–close. Weekend hours: 11 AM–close. One-day pass: approximately $50 for adults/riders 48"+. Visit palaceplayland.com for current pricing.</p>

	<h2>The Boardwalk Strip</h2>

	<p>Old Orchard Street and the beachfront strip form the classic seaside carnival experience: arcades, ring toss, fried dough, cotton candy, saltwater taffy, mini golf. This is the heartbeat of OOB in summer. The strip runs at full capacity July through Labor Day weekend.</p>

	<p>A few shopping spots worth noting: <strong>Beachology</strong> for locally made gifts and apparel; <strong>Dickinson's Candy</strong> for handmade chocolates; <strong>Maine Country Woods</strong> for artisan wooden crafts.</p>

	<h2>Dining in OOB</h2>

	<h3>For a casual beachside meal</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Pier French Fries</strong> — thick-cut fries, fried dough, and hot dogs at the pier since 1932</li>
		<li><strong>JJ's Eatery</strong> — the best breakfast spot near the pier</li>
		<li><strong>Jake's Eatery Too</strong> — corned beef hash, housemade pancakes, Irish Benny</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>For a lobster roll</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Johnny Shucks Maine Lobster</strong> — well-reviewed for freshness</li>
		<li><strong>Bell Buoy</strong> — hot buttered lobster roll</li>
		<li><strong>Big Daddy's Bar & Grill</strong> — lobster sandwich on crescent roll</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>For a proper dinner</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Joseph's By the Sea</strong> — OOB's fine dining standard for 50+ years, with rooftop and dining room ocean views; worth booking ahead in July</li>
		<li><strong>Pirates Patio & Galley</strong> — tables set in the sand; cocktails and American grill</li>
		<li><strong>Surf 6 Oceanfront Grille & Bar</strong> — beachfront dining with live entertainment</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Nightlife</h2>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Top of the Pier Nightclub</strong> — the iconic OOB night-out spot, with a Sunset Deck</li>
		<li><strong>GFB Scottish Pub</strong> (32 Old Orchard St) — the only brewpub in OOB; craft beers and pub fare daily from 5 PM</li>
		<li><strong>Myst Oceanside Restaurant & Lounge</strong> — open May–September until 1 AM Fri/Sat; frozen cocktails and live music</li>
		<li><strong>Water's Edge Tiki Bar</strong> — tropical cocktails and a laid-back vibe</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Weekly Events</h2>

	<p><strong>Thursday Night Fireworks:</strong> Professional fireworks launch from the beach near the Pier every Thursday night from late June through late August at approximately 9:45 PM. Free to watch from anywhere on the main beach.</p>

	<p><strong>Rock the Park Concerts:</strong> Free outdoor concerts at The Ballpark, 7 Ballpark Way. Gates open 5 PM; music 6–8 PM. All summer long on select evenings.</p>

	<h2>When to Visit</h2>

	<p><strong>Peak season (July–August):</strong> Full energy, all rides open, weekly fireworks, every restaurant operating. Also: highest prices, biggest crowds, most difficult parking.</p>

	<p><strong>September:</strong> The underrated option. Water is often warmer than July. Crowds thin dramatically after Labor Day. Most restaurants stay open. Hotel rates drop. The Car Show (mid-September) is a bonus. If you care more about a comfortable beach experience than peak-season intensity, September is the answer.</p>

	<p><strong>Memorial Day weekend and early June:</strong> Most things open, smaller crowds, lower prices. A few businesses not yet at full operation.</p>

	<h2>The French-Canadian Connection</h2>

	<p>An estimated 30–40% of OOB's summer visitors are Canadian, primarily from Quebec. This goes back to 1853, when the Grand Trunk Railroad connected Montreal to the region. OOB is geographically the closest Atlantic beach to both Quebec City and Montreal. Bilingual signage and French-speaking staff are common throughout downtown; the Canadian flag flies outside many properties. It's a cultural fact of the place worth knowing before you arrive.</p>

	<h2>Day Trips from OOB</h2>

	<p><strong>Portland (20 minutes north):</strong> The Old Port district has cobblestone streets, excellent restaurants, and craft breweries. Portland Head Light at Cape Elizabeth — Maine's oldest lighthouse, commissioned by George Washington in 1791 — is 20 minutes from OOB and one of the most photographed spots in New England.</p>

	<p><strong>Kennebunkport (25–30 minutes south):</strong> Upscale coastal village known for Dock Square boutiques, Goose Rocks Beach, and whale watching tours to Jeffrey's Ledge offshore.</p>

	<p><strong>Biddeford (10 minutes from Saco Bay Hotel):</strong> One of New England's most surprising food scenes — James Beard-nominated chefs, a 1927 Pollard dining car turned acclaimed restaurant (Palace Diner), and a fully revitalized downtown that Food & Wine Magazine named one of the next great food cities. A short drive from the hotel for a very different dinner experience.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Base Yourself in Saco</strong>
		<p>Saco Bay Hotel is two miles from the OOB pier — close enough to be at the beach in five minutes, far enough to avoid the resort-town crowds and pricing. You get the full Old Orchard experience with the option to retreat when you've had enough of the noise. Most of our guests split their days between the beach, Funtown Splashtown USA (1.5 miles away), and dinner in Biddeford.</p>
	</div>
